{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves meaning, not literal word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real neural model output quality (fluency/meaning preservation), which a deterministic mock cannot validate. This is a single model-step quality assertion, not a multi-step agent session.","test_description":"Run the service against the real translation model/API on a curated multilingual set with idioms and non-literal phrasing; score semantic adequacy and fluency (human rubric or semantic metric threshold) and fail if output is literal-but-wrong or meaning is lost.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"On translation API 503, service transparently falls back to dictionary translator and does not return error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"To catch real failures in HTTP status handling, retry/error mapping, and fallback triggering, the test should exercise a real HTTP boundary. In-process mocks can hide miswired status/exception handling.","test_description":"Start the service with a test SQLite dictionary and point primary translator client to a local HTTP test server that returns 503. Verify caller gets 200-style successful response with fallback translation payload and no propagated upstream error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Dictionary fallback returns correct pre-stored translation for phrases present in SQLite.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is SQL/schema/query wiring plus lookup logic. Mocking DB could miss incorrect SQL, transaction, or collation behavior.","test_description":